    "Example 2.1: Simplest example of non-trivial 1-chargeThe simplest non-trivial irreducible 2-representation arises forG (0) = 2, (27)which isρ (2) = (H = 1, [σ] = 0).",
    "(28)To realize it physically, we need a multiplet of two simple line operators L and L ′, or in other words a non-simple line operatorL ⊕ L ′.",
    "(29)The action of ( 27) then exchanges L and L ′.",
    "In fact, 2 has only two irreducible 2representations, with the other 2-representation being the trivial oneρ (2) = (H = 2, [σ] = 0),(30)which is physically realized on a single simple line operatorL,(31)which is left invariant by the action of ( 27).",
